//The logic behind this is it's a one time pad and we don't know the key, but we know the key is 50k chars long because we have access to the code that does the encryption
//knowing that we pass a ridiculous amount of a character we know, a in this case and since we know the flag is 32 characters long because the encrypted flag is 
//64 hex digits long. So what we need to do is wrap around and perform an XOR to get the plaintext flag because the encrypted a and the encrypted flag would have the
//same part of the key applied to them. We use 49968 because the first 32 digits were already used by the plaintext flag.

maxap-picoctf@webshell:~$ python -c "print('a'*49968);print('a'*32)" | nc mercury.picoctf.net 36981
